Load-bearing architecture facts (don't re-derive these)

src/modules.lua:11 → M.api = getfenv() — m.api IS the global table _G.
main.lua → M.api = function() return m.api end.
Dependency injection everywhere — each component takes its dependencies as constructor args.
src/Interface.lua → interface.validate(impl, interface_table) checks each key exists and type(v) == expected_type. CRITICAL LIMITATION: presence-only. It does NOT check arity or return shape. This is precisely why the original porting bugs (wrong arity / wrong return count) were invisible to the test suite — the mocks encode the same wrong assumptions the code does.
Version flags: on this fork m.wotlk = true; m.vanilla / m.bcc are unset (verified in src/wotlk/compat.lua; a vanilla compat file exists in the repo but is not loaded by the TOC). compat.lua also provides the SOUNDKIT shim + PlaySound polyfill. src/wotlk/backport.lua provides IsInGroup and documents the leader-check behavior.
GameApi adapter (new): src/GameApi.lua / m.GameApi wraps _G and exposes normalized primitives, injected as M.game_api in place of M.api(). Validated via Interface.validate against m.WowApi.GameApiInterface (raw side) and m.GameApi.interface (normalized side).

The boundary rule (keeps the adapter from becoming a second god-object)
The adapter normalizes the WoW API surface — signatures, return shapes, presence checks. It does NOT encode domain decisions.
get_loot_method() returning a clean record → adapter. is_master_looter() composing that record + roster lookup + name compare → stays in PlayerInfo.

