Comms — the big one (NEW; #1 reliability lever toward S-tier)
There are two parallel addon-comms stacks in the codebase right now:

Vanilla RollFor independently built RollForBroadcast / RollForReceiver on AceComm-3.0 + LibSerialize — robust; the library handles message fragmentation and ChatThrottleLib throttling for you.
WotLK fork inherited sica's Client / ClientBroadcast — manual SendAddonMessage chunking; fragile around throttling, size limits, and mixed-version raids.

Both currently coexist; the TOC controls which one loads.
Target: migrate the WotLK fork onto the AceComm + LibSerialize stack (adopt vanilla's RollForBroadcast / RollForReceiver), replacing the hand-rolled chunking. This is the single biggest reliability win available. Considerations when we get there:

Verify AceComm-3.0 + LibSerialize are embedded and working in the WotLK libs (both run fine on 3.3.5a; widely used by mature addons).
Swap the TOC to load RollForBroadcast/RollForReceiver and stop loading Client/ClientBroadcast.
Rewire ClientBroadcast consumers to the new API.
Preserve a protocol/version handshake so mixed-version raids degrade gracefully (a version_broadcast new-version check already exists).
Self-contained migration: WotLK clients only talk to other WotLK clients, so there's no cross-version protocol concern with the vanilla addon.


